<DOC><DOCNO> AP881102-0285 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1356EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Wickes     11-02 0241</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Wickes,0251</SECOND><HEAD>Buyer May Sell Retail, Credit Operations</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The prospective buyers of Wickes Cos. say theyare considering breaking up the company and selling retail andcredit operations, including Wickes Furniture and Builders Emporium,if their bid succeeds.   The Blackstone Group and Wasserstein, Perella andamp; Co., New Yorkinvestor groups which launched a $538.9 million buyout Tuesday,disclosed their intent to sell parts of the company in a filing withthe Securities and Exchange Commission.   The takeover, negotiated with management, will be accomplishedthrough an $11.25 per share tender offer to stockholders.   ``The purchaser expects to sell a significant amount of thecompany's assets,'' according to a registration statement for thetender offer. ``Based on information currently available to it, thepurchaser expects to sell most or all of the company's retail andcredit operations.''   The statement says the tentative decision to sell variousoperations may be reversed or altered.   The retailers, Wickes Furniture, Builders Emporium homeimprovement stores, and Orchard Supply Hardware stores, accountedfor about 31 percent of the company's sales last year. The creditoperations offer financing for the retail stores.   Wickes other operations include automotive products, wallpaper,fabrics and the Kayser-Roth hosiery and apparel units.   Blackstone and Wasserstein, Perella executives will replaceSanford Sigoloff, the Wickes chairman who saved the company frombankruptcy and sought to take it private in a leveraged buyout thatled to the investor groups' successful takeover bid.</TEXT></DOC>